thread.title: Michigan State stuns Michigan, 27-23, on fumbled punt on final play
thread.title_full: Michigan State stuns Michigan, 27-23, on fumbled punt on final play | The Seattle Times

author: Joe Rexrode
title: Michigan State stuns Michigan, 27-23, on fumbled punt on final play
text:
ANN ARBOR, Mich. — Don’t bother flipping through the history books — there has never been a crazier finish in the Michigan State-Michigan rivalry than the one that just took place at Michigan Stadium.
Michigan punter Blake O’Neill lined up for a game-sealing punt with 10 seconds left and Michigan leading 23-21, but he fumbled the snap, took a hit and the ball went into the hands of MSU’s Jalen Watts-Jackson — who streaked all the way for a 38-yard touchdown on the final play of the game to lift MSU to a 27-23 victory.
UMBELIEVABLE pic.twitter.com/di7DqaK9ms 
— Rob Perez (@World_Wide_Wob) October 17, 2015

“Football is a crazy, crazy game,” Spartans coach Mark Dantonio said. “You can’t hardly explain it.”
A stadium full of U-M fans expecting to revel in a gigantic rivalry win instead had to watch as the Spartans celebrated wildly in the north end zone.
“A mistake was made,” Michigan coach Jim Harbaugh said. “Mistakes were made. It’s very unfortunate circumstances.”
A Michigan State official said Watts-Jackson dislocated his hip after diving into the end zone for the winning score but that it popped back into place. He was taken to a hospital.
Somehow, the No. 7 Spartans (7-0, 3-0 Big Ten) remain alive for their Big Ten title and College Football Playoff pursuits.
Before that stunning play, Michigan State senior quarterback Connor Cook came up empty in his attempt to bring the Spartans back. His deep pass to an open Macgarrett Kings Jr. on fourth-and-19 hung up and was broken up by Michigan’s Dymonte Thomas to seemingly deliver a win for No. 12 Michigan (5-2, 2-1).
Cook threw for 328 yards and a touchdown and Aaron Burbridge had 132 yards receiving.
Joe Rexrode
